  "reasoning": "I'll start by fetching the FRED data and checking for any previous forecasts, then run a Monte Carlo simulation.Good, I have the data. Now let me run a Monte Carlo simulation using the empirical daily changes.Now let me also check if there's any notable recent market news that might affect TIPS yields, and check if Feb 25 data might actually be reported (it's a Wednesday, should be a normal trading day).The bootstrap uses the empirical distribution which has near-zero drift and captures the actual jump distribution well. Let me also check for any data that may have been published after Feb 12.Now let me write my meta-reflection and provide the final forecast.**Forecast Summary for DFII30 on 2026-02-25:**\n\nThe 30-Year TIPS yield was **2.48%** on Feb 12 (latest data). Resolution is 8 trading days later on Feb 25.\n\n| Percentile | Value |\n|-----------|-------|\n| 10th | 2.38% |\n| 20th | 2.42% |\n| 40th | 2.46% |\n| 60th | 2.50% |\n| 80th | 2.54% |\n| 90th | 2.58% |\n\n**Key reasoning:**\n- Daily volatility is ~2.7bp with near-zero drift over 3.5 months → random walk model applies\n- Bootstrap Monte Carlo from 68 empirical daily changes gives a symmetric distribution centered at ~2.48%\n- Recent 15bp decline (2.63→2.48) is notable but could revert or continue — the bootstrap captures both scenarios\n- 80% confidence interval spans roughly 12bp in each direction, consistent with σ_daily × √8 ≈ 7.5bp",
